orbit_10_page_class_notes-73b1ae1f.docx.text: These notes are designed to simulate real classroom notes used by students for revision and study.
Artificial Intelligence (AI) is one of the fastest-growing areas in computer science. It focuses on building systems that can perform tasks which normally require human intelligence.
Artificial Intelligence refers to the ability of machines to imitate intelligent human behavior.
The term AI was first coined in 1956 during the Dartmouth Conference.
AI systems can analyze data, recognize patterns, and make decisions with minimal human intervention.
Examples of AI include search engines, recommendation systems, and voice assistants.
1950s–1960s: Early symbolic AI and rule-based systems.
1990s–2000s: Machine learning gained popularity due to better data availability.
2010s–Present: Deep learning and large-scale neural networks dominate the field.
Narrow AI: Designed to perform a specific task such as image recognition.
General AI: A theoretical form of AI capable of performing any intellectual task a human can.
Super AI: Hypothetical AI that surpasses human intelligence in all aspects.
Currently, all existing AI systems fall under Narrow AI.
Machine Learning is a subset of AI that focuses on systems that learn from data.
Instead of explicit programming, ML models identify patterns automatically.
Unsupervised learning works with unlabeled data.
Reinforcement learning is based on rewards and penalties.
Deep Learning is a subset of Machine Learning that uses neural networks with multiple layers.
Inspired by the structure of the human brain.
Common architectures include CNNs, RNNs, and Transformers.
Deep learning performs well on image, audio, and text data.
Data is the foundation of all AI systems.
High-quality data leads to better model performance.
Data preprocessing includes cleaning, normalization, and transformation.
Biased data can result in unfair or incorrect AI decisions.
Healthcare: Disease detection and medical imaging.
Finance: Fraud detection and algorithmic trading.
The importance of responsible AI development.
Need for human oversight and regulation.
Artificial Intelligence aims to replicate human intelligence in machines.
Machine Learning and Deep Learning are key subfields of AI.
Data quality directly impacts AI performance.
Ethical considerations are critical for real-world deployment.
AI will continue to shape the future across multiple industries.

orbit_10_page_class_notes-73b1ae1f.docx.text: This script uses the python-docx library to create a 10-page document that mimics the style of messy, hurried student notes (including abbreviations, "Important" markers, and bullet points).
Here is how you can do it.
This script creates a file named Psychology_101_Notes.docx. It forces page breaks to ensure you get exactly 10 pages of content covering a "Introduction to Psychology" course.
Prerequisites: You need Python installed. You also need to install the python-docx library.
# helper function to add a lecture header
run.font.name = 'Courier New' # Looks a bit more like typewritten/raw notes
# helper to add normal note text
add_note("Prof said syllabus is on the portal. DO NOT forget to sign up for research credits (SONA systems).")
add_note("What is Psych? -> Scientific study of mind and behavior.")
add_note("- Wundt (1879): First lab in Leipzig. 'Father of Psych'. Used Introspection.")
add_note("    -> Problem with introspection: It's subjective! People lie or don't know why they feel things.")
add_note("- Structuralism (Titchener): Breaking mind into basic elements. (Like chemistry tables?)")
add_note("- Functionalism (James): Stream of consciousness. WHY do we think? Adapted from Darwin.")
add_note("Hindsight Bias: 'I knew it all along' phenomenon.")
add_note("1. Theory\n2. Hypothesis (testable prediction)\n3. Operational Definitions (very imp!! how do we measure 'happiness'? Smiles/hour?)")
add_note("* Descriptive: Case studies (Phineas Gage!), Surveys, Naturalistic Observation.")
add_note("    -> CORRELATION IS NOT CAUSATION. Ice cream sales correlates w/ shark attacks (confounding var: heat).")
add_note("* Experimental: Manipulation. IV vs DV. Control group vs Experimental group.")
add_note("- Myelin Sheath: Fatty tissue, speeds up signal. (MS = degeneration of myelin)")
add_note("Action Potential: All-or-none response. Electrical impulse.")
add_note("Synapse: Gap between neurons. Neurotransmitters swim across.")
add_note("1. Dopamine (Reward/Movement) -> Too much = Schizo, Too little = Parkinsons")
add_note("- Amygdala: Fear/Aggression (size of a bean)")
add_note("- Hypothalamus: The 4 Fs (Feeding, Fighting, Fleeing... Mating). Maintains homeostasis.")
add_note("Cortex is the wrinkled outer layer. Glial cells = spider webs supporting neurons.")
add_note("1. Frontal: Planning, judgment, personality (Phineas Gage again). Motor strip.")
add_note("3. Occipital: Vision (back of head). Hit hard -> see stars.")
